F2: I like the idea of delineating policy goals, and describing, line by line, the objectives that would allow that goal to be measured, worked on, and achieved. The issue that gives me pause is that there are several objectives that I would want more clarification about before I could definitively say, “yes, I support that”, or “actually no, I hate that, now that I know specifically what that would entail”. I like the idea of advancing policy goals that are agreed upon and would benefit the majority of Americans, regardless of how they might identify in terms of political party. But several objectives within this app seemed heavily focused on economic efficiency, productivity, and de-regulation (without specifics on which regulations are being reduced/removed, hypothetically). Some of the stated objectives appeal to me, but several seem more focused on the economy, productivity, and metrics of efficiency, and those things cannot and do not typically tell the whole story about the well-being of a populace. (If this app is, for example, what Elon Musk was describing re: his vision for the creation of a new political party, I would not be surprised, as I feel it is very heavily focused on “efficiency” and economic metrics, and not as focused on deeply broken systems (health care, education, etc) that are failing people in real-time, specifically *because* costs have been cut to the penny, and the system is ostensibly still trying to provide services, but the services suck, precisely because the systems are so grossly understaffed and under-funded. I hope that the creators of this app would be open to the idea that taking an “all business” approach to governance would deeply miss the mark.
